    <name>
      <text>Relationship between the side lengths and areas of similar regular hexagons</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>
The corresponding sides of two similar regular hexagons are \( {@s1@} \) and \( {@s2@} \) respectively.</p>
<p><b>(a)</b> Find the ratio of their areas.<br>
[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]
</p>
<p>(b).  </b>If the area of the smaller hexagon is \( {@A_small@} \), calculate the area of the larger hexagon.<br> <b>Note:</b> Write your answer correct to 2 decimal places
[[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]
</p>
<p>.</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3>Worked Solution</h3>
<p>Determine the linear scale factor</p>
<p>The side lengths of the similar regular hexagons are:<p>
<p>Small hexagon: \( {@s1@} \)</p>
<p>Large hexagon: \( {@s2@} \)</p>
<p>The linear scale factor from the smaller to the larger hexagon is</p>

<p>\(k = \frac{@s2@}{@s1@}.\)</p>

<p>Ratio of their areas</p>
<p>For any pair of similar shapes, the ratio of their areas is the square of the ratio of their corresponding side lengths.  
Thus,</p>

<p>\(\text{Area ratio} = k^2 = \left(\frac{@s2@}{@s1@}\right)^2 = {@ratio_area@}.
\)</p>

<p> Area of the larger hexagon</p>
<p>We are told that the area of the smaller hexagon  = {@A_small@}.

<p>To find the area of the larger hexagon, multiply by the area ratio:</p>

<p>\(A_{\text{large}}= A_{\text{small}} \cdot k^2= {@A_small@} \cdot {@ratio_area@}
= {@A_large@}.
\)</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
